<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="play">
<PB REF="4">
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT I.</HEAD>
<STAGE>SCENE,&mdash;<HI>A Room at an Inn.</HI>&mdash;HEARTWELL <HI>di&s;covered a&s;leep in an Undre&s;s on a Sopha;</HI> JUBA <HI>&s;itting by him, playing on a Guittar.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<STAGE>After the Tune, HEARTWELL wakes,</STAGE>
<P>JUBA!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JUBA.</SPEAKER>
<P>You call, Ma&s;&s;a?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>How long have I been a&s;leep?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JUBA.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;leep long time, Ma&s;&s;a; mo&s;t two hour; &s;leep do you good; you better now, Ma&s;&s;a; Juba glad you better.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>How unfortunate was this acci|dent during my &s;earch after Caroline! whil&s;t I was every hour in hopes of tracing out the place to which her father has conveyed her, to be laid up in my bed for &s;ix days in an inn; without money, without friends, without&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JUBA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't you &s;orry, Ma&s;&s;a; I your friend,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor little fellow! I have no power at pre&s;ent to reward thee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JUBA.</SPEAKER>
<P>You good to me, Ma&s;&s;a, when I come from my own country&mdash;you very good when I &s;ick; no mind you no money, you have money bine by.</P>
</SP>
<Q><PB N="6" REF="5">
<TEXT>
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG.</HEAD>
<LG>
<L>You care of money, care no more,</L>
<L>No tink if you be rich or poor,</L>
<L>My mind employ;</L>
<L>Me &s;tay with you; no &s;orry, no!</L>
<L>And where away my Ma&s;&s;a go,</L>
<L>Go poor black boy.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>You good to me, dat keepy here;</L>
<L>No, Ma&s;&s;a! dat you never fear;</L>
<L>Long time de&s;troy:</L>
<L>You know death kill, but leave one part,</L>
<L>He never kill de loving heart</L>
<L>Of poor black boy!</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>This kind creature's gratitude for the freedom I procured for him is without bounds.</P>
<STAGE>(Juba bowing)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who are you bowing to there?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JUBA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ma&s;&s;a Lenitive, your doctor, he come here:</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm not more tired of my &s;ick room than I am of my apothecary; in a coun|try town one is glad of any a&s;&s;i&s;tance that can be met with; but never, &s;ure, was there &s;uch a mixture of ignorance and profe&s;&s;ional im|portance, as in this fellow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JUBA.</SPEAKER>
<P>He come to door on &s;tair now, Ma&s;&s;a.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now then, for my ears to be dinn'd with a battery of technical terms. I'll di&s;mi&s;s him to-day, I'm determin'd.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="7" REF="6">
<HI>Enter</HI> LENITIVE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Heartwell, your obedient! you &s;lept well, doubtle&s;s, on the bal&s;amick?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thanks to your care and &s;kill, Mr. Lenitive; I'm not quite well.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>By no means, Sir! Ye&s;terday our pul&s;e intimated an approximation to conva|le&s;cence; but we are yet much di&s;orderd. Did you take tho&s;e little medicines that I ordered you this morning?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, and want nothing now but fre&s;h air to &s;trengthen me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Give me leave, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Sits down by him on the &s;opha, pulls out his watch and feels</HI> Heartwell<HI>'s pul&s;e.</HI></STAGE>
<P>You mu&s;t keep your&s;elf remarkably quiet; and not &s;uffer any one to &s;peak to you: in all ca&s;e. Mr. Heartwell, of a &s;imilar nature to your's, where either laceration or extrava&s;ation takes place on the membranous or cartilaginous fibres&mdash;the&mdash;you'll excu&s;eme, Sir&mdash;I'm afraid I don't make my&s;elf perfectly under&s;tood?</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed you do not! <STAGE>(a&s;ide).</STAGE> Oh, perfectly, Sir! Go on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>I ju&s;t remark'd, Sir, that where a &s;y&s;tole or dia&s;tole is cau&s;ed by any affection of the interco&s;tal mu&s;cles or the diaphragm, in tho&s;e ca&s;es.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LABEL.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>A letter for you, Sir,</P>
<STAGE>(to Lenitive)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ble&s;s my &s;oul! you'll excu&s;e me, Mr.
<PB N="8" REF="7">Heartwell&mdash;&s;ome ca&s;e of importance&mdash;I'm &s;o overcharg'd with patients&mdash;great rapidity of ideas, Captain, requi&s;ite fora medicinal per&s;on &mdash;one moment weighing the vibration of the nerves, and another diving into the vi&s;cera!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>A mi&s;take might, I pre&s;ume, be dangerous?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fatal, Sir&mdash;ab&s;olutely fatal! An ac|cident of the kind happened here la&s;t week&mdash; Doctor Lancet, my opponent&mdash;for merit, Sir&mdash;you know, Sir, merit every where has its &s;hadow&mdash;Doctor Lancet, Sir, ordered a me|dicine &s;typtic, conge&s;tive, and anticathartick, which he intended to go directly to the lungs &mdash;but, unfortunately, not recollecting that his patient's complaint lay in the plexus hep|taticus, and not in the pulmonaria&mdash;the me|dicine, to be &s;ure, did its bu&s;ine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>And the patient's bu&s;ine&s;s too, I &s;uppo&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Exactly &s;o, Sir&mdash;Ha! ha! ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! ha! ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>You'll excu&s;e my young man&mdash;Ha! ha! fond of a joke&mdash;Eh, Label! it was exactly &s;o, Sir&mdash;I am cautious in &s;aying it&mdash;but you'll excu&s;e me whil&s;t I read this&mdash;the ca&s;e perhaps is pre&s;&s;ing&mdash;Od&s;o! an expre&s;s from London! a con&s;ultation probably&mdash;nothing more u&s;ual Eh, Label! you know, nothing more common?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh no, nothing&mdash;nothing more common with us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN. <HI>(reads)</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>"Sir, your ticket"&mdash;So, &s;o! an account of one of my lottery tickets&mdash; <STAGE>(<HI>ri&s;es</HI>)</STAGE> "Sir, your ticket in the Engli&s;h lottery,
<PB N="9" REF="8">No. 78, was on the tenth day drawn&mdash;a blank!" &mdash;Um! always dabbling in the lottery; never &s;hall have any luck!&mdash;"And your ticket, No. 2, 5, 3, 8, was this day drawn a prize of Ten Thou&s;and Pounds principal money!"&mdash;Ble&s;s my&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>But pray, Doctor&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ten thou&s;and Pounds! <STAGE>(jumps about in extacy.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>But pray, now, Mr. Lenitive&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>No. 2, 5, 3, 8! a lucky number in|deed! I know what I'll do with it&mdash;But I'll keep it a &s;ecret. <STAGE>(apart.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, what po&s;&s;e&s;&s;es the man! but I &s;ay, Doctor Lenitive&mdash; <STAGE>(ri&s;es and follows him about.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! I had forgot my patient! <STAGE>(re|&s;uming his gravity.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Any orders for the &s;hop, Sir.?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damn the &s;hop!&mdash;Eh! what! no, no&mdash;I &s;hall return pre&s;ently.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>"Damn the &s;hop!"&mdash;why, I never heard &s;uch&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit muttering,</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>You'll excu&s;e me, Sir&mdash;but a ca&s;e that was particularly intere&s;ting&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>A &s;ucce&s;sful one, I pre&s;ume, by the violent &s;ymptoms of your joy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir, very &s;ucce&s;sful indeed: more than I cou'd expect.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's the fir&s;t mode&s;t word I ever heard him &s;peak of him&s;elf. <STAGE>(<HI>a&s;ide.</HI>)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>2, 5, 3, 8! But I forget my patient &mdash;I think you were &s;aying, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="10" REF="9">
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>I was &s;aying, Sir, that I find my&s;elf &s;o much recover'd as to have no longer need to trouble you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Give me leave, give me leave, Sir; <STAGE>(feels his pul&s;e.)</STAGE> Why, ay, Sir, your ticket&mdash; poh! your fever, I mean, Sir&mdash;Yes, your fever, as you &s;ay, is quite &s;ub&s;ided&mdash;yes&mdash;ble&s;s me, how lucky! Ten Thou&s;and Pound! quite &s;ub|&s;ided, yes, I &s;ay, quite&mdash;However, I wou'd advi&s;e you to continue on your couch another day, Sir&mdash;Ten Thou&s;and! how I &s;hall a&s;to|ni&s;h Mr. Caddy with the news; and my dear Mi&s;s Caroline too&mdash;But&mdash;Zounds, I forgot my patient! I cou'd wi&s;h you, Sir, let me con|&s;ider&mdash;I can't think how I &s;hall get the mo|ney &s;ent down to me&mdash;I cou'd wi&s;h you not to go out to-day, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Sir, as you plea&s;e; for one day more, but mu&s;t I continue my draughts?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Drafts! egad, well thought on! I'd bet|ter have it &s;ent down in drafts&mdash;drafts! yes, Sir&mdash;no, no&mdash;I&mdash;I &s;hall &s;end you &s;ome drops to take.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>But what number?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Number Two Thou&s;and Five Hundred and Thirty Eight&mdash;a mo&s;t lucky number!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Two thou&s;and drops! why, zounds I &s;hou'd be all day in counting 'em!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Count&mdash;no, no, Sir&mdash;I mean&mdash;no, nine or ten drops&mdash;nine or ten will be quite &s;ufficient&mdash;I forgot my patient indeed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why &s;ure the man's crazy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>You'll excu&s;e me, Captain, but I'm engag'd to attend Mr. Caddy, and &s;hall &s;ee
<PB N="11" REF="10">you again in the afternoon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Caddy, Sir&mdash;Is he in the neighbourhood?</P>
<STAGE>(eagerly.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>He has a hou&s;e near here, Sir, of which he has lately taken po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion; famous for one of the &s;ine&s;t collection of Chine&s;e curio&s;i|ties in Europe; which I am my&s;elf going to en|rich to day with&mdash;Ten Thou&s;and Pound! I mean&mdash;a celebrated figure of Chine&s;e Bonze, or High Prie&s;t&mdash;I'll give you a particular ac|count of it&mdash;A&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Another time if you plea&s;e. Pray, Mr. Lenitive, has Mr. Caddy a daughter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Two thou&s;and five hundred and thir|ty-eight!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>How! what!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Od&s;o! a&s;k pardon, Sir&mdash;Daughter! yes, Sir Mi&s;s Caroline, a mo&s;t accompli&s;hed and amiable young lady&mdash;Well, you'll con|tinue in your room to-day.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>You'll excu&s;e me, Sir&mdash;Juba! my things to dre&s;s!</P>
<STAGE>(In raptures&mdash;Exit Juba.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ble&s;s me! his fever's returned! My dear Sir&mdash;you mu&s;t not think of &s;tirring out to day&mdash;for&mdash;Ten thou&s;and Pound!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>But I mu&s;t&mdash;I hope my journey will produce double the &s;um&mdash;How Fortunate.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fortunate indeed, Sir&mdash;a&s;toni&s;hingly fortunate&mdash;but, dear Sir, you are not aware, that by expo&s;ing your&s;elf thus &s;uddenly to the inclemency of the atmo&s;phere&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray leave me now, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>You'll clo&s;e the reticula of the cutis.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be gone, I &s;ay!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="12" REF="11">
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be gone! Oh, yes! he's quite delirious &mdash;but con&s;ider, Sir, the coagulation of the juices.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zounds! depart, I &s;ay.</P>
<STAGE>(driving him off.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>For a &s;trait wai&s;tcoat&mdash;take care, Sir, how you bring on a con&s;tipation of the fluids.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Death and fire! get out.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>And at the termination of the com|plaint, produce a mortification of the noblen inter&s;tines; which will finally compleat the di&s;&s;olution of the &s;y&s;tem.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ten thou&s;and Devils fly away with you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ten thou&s;and pounds! 2, 5, 3 8!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Exit.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>This fellow's certainly mad! there's no end to his impertinence!&mdash;Juba!
<STAGE>(<HI>Enter</HI> JUBA.)</STAGE> Bring me pen, ink, and paper directly and go again to the po&s;t-office.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit</HI> JUBA.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now for my Caroline&mdash;the hope of &s;eeing her revives me to life, health, and &s;pirits.&mdash;This blockhead Lenitive, has done me &s;ome good at la&s;t.</P>
<STAGE>(Exit,)</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE>SCENE. <HI>The out&s;ide of a Hou&s;e in a Rural Situation&mdash;</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE>CAROLINE <HI>di&s;covered at the Window after throwing up the &s;a&s;h.</HI></STAGE>
<Q><TEXT>
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>AIR AND DUET.</HEAD>
<L>Ah, tell me &s;oftly-breathing gale,</L>
<L>Did you my voice obey?</L>
<L>Ah, did you tell the plaintive tale?</L>
<L>The tender &s;igh convey?</L>
<L><PB N="13" REF="12">
Ah, faithle&s;s gales! ye were unkind,</L>
<L>Ye did no &s;ighs convey.</L>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> JUBA.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JUBA.</SPEAKER>
<L>What &s;ingy! hark! &s;o much me plea&s;e,</L>
<L>How mu&s;ic &s;et my heart at ea&s;e!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Juba!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JUBA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is it you? or only fancy no tell true.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<L>Go ha&s;te to let thy ma&s;ter know</L>
<L>The tran&s;port of my mind!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JUBA.</SPEAKER>
<L>That voice me &s;ure have in my mind,</L>
<L>Who fingy there I pray?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<L>Ah, may I hope, if he return</L>
<L>A con&s;tant heart to find?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="14" REF="13">
<SPEAKER>JUBA.</SPEAKER>
<L>Me ha&s;te to let my Ma&s;&s;a know</L>
<L>The tran&s;port of your mind, &amp;c. &amp;c.</L>
<P>Ah Mi&s;&s;y! me glad to &s;ee you; poor Ma&s;&s;a be very glad.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is Mr. Heartwell in this town? where is he? how does he do?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JUBA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ifs, Mi&s;&s;y! Ma&s;&s;a here at an inn clo&s;e by; he &s;end me to po&s;t a great many time&mdash; me bring no letter, ma&s;&s;a be &s;ad&mdash;but he not.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Mrs CADDY <HI>without,</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Caroline!</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>calling.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ma'am!&mdash;What is he not? Juba.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Caroline, where are you all this while?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Coming this in&s;tant, Ma'am&mdash;But, Juba, tell me of Heartwell&mdash;isn't he well?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JUBA.</SPEAKER>
<P>He no well now, Mi&s;&s;y; but he well when he &s;ee you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Caroline, come down directly, and &s;hut the window.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Coming, Mamma&mdash;Juba, ha&s;te to your ma&s;ter, tell him my father has &s;elected an odious apothecary to be my hu&s;band; but that I'm determin'd I wont have him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Caroline, I &s;ay&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Coming, Mamma!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JUBA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very well, Mi&s;&s;y! me tell him&mdash;dis
<PB N="15" REF="14">do my Ma&s;&s;a heart good&mdash;dis better dan eat and drink, and potecary's &s;tuff too&mdash;me go tell my Ma&s;&s;a dis now, go to po&s;t by and by.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit,</HI> CAROLINE <HI>&s;huts the window.</HI>)</STAGE>
<STAGE>SCENE, <HI>an Apothecary's Shop&mdash;Phy&s;ic, Phials, &amp;c</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LENITIVE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ten thou&s;and pounds! wherefore &s;hou'd I be an apothecary? Poh! throw phy&s;ic to the dogs! I'll be a gentleman! if I marry Mi&s;s Caroline, with the addition of <HI>her</HI> fortune, I &s;hall make one of the fine&s;t figures in the univer&s;e! I was born to gentility! <STAGE>(<HI>&s;truts</HI>)</STAGE> I feel it in my veins&mdash;in my bones&mdash;and the whole ma&s;s of my circulation&mdash;But the opening of <HI>my</HI> fortune, ay, that's the point&mdash;it wou'd be a nice hit if I cou'd devi&s;e &s;ome recipe to &s;ur|pri&s;e Mr. Caddy's family &s;martly at the time of di&s;covery&mdash;a few grains of the bele&s;prit on this occa&s;ion may operate in my favour.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>During this &s;peech Label enters, and attempts to &s;peak &s;everal times to Lenitive, at la&s;t pulls him by the &s;leeve,</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir! Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! Label!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>You've been very much wanted here, Sir; Lady Blubber and Mrs Re&s;tles have &s;ent to de&s;ire you'd come directly to'em&mdash;I've been up at Mrs Neverwell's&mdash;I'm afraid that will turn out a bad job&mdash;&s;he has taken every pre&s;cription in our day-book&mdash;and I don't
<PB N="16" REF="15">know what more can be done for the poor crea|ture&mdash;&s;he was piteous bad, and crying out with pain!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>During the &s;peech Lenitive appear ab&s;orbed and un|mindful of Label's &s;peaking; and at la&s;t bursts our into a loud laugh.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>How! what does it divert you Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>That will do! I have got an excel|lent thought ju&s;t come in my head!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm glad of it, for they're all de&s;|perate &s;ad,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I have it!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dearme, I'm glad of it! D'ye think you can cure her &s;ir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>How it will &s;urpri&s;e 'em!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, that will &s;urpri&s;e 'em indeed and I'm &s;ure it will yield great joy to the whole family.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh! why yes as you &s;ay, Label! they'll all enjoy it mightily. I'll tell you how I'll manage it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Sir</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>You know I have promis'd to give Mr. Caddy an old Chine&s;e figure: which I have told him is a High Prie&s;t embalm'd&mdash; now, as this is a curious ca&s;e&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Quite puzzling, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll &s;end him two in&s;tead of one&mdash;&s;o do you go to the carpenter's?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>The carpenter's!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, to be &s;ure the carpenter's!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, dear Sir, the poor lady's &s;itua|tion
<PB N="17" REF="16">won't admit of delay; for I warrant you &s;he's in fits again by this time.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fits! who's in fits?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nrs. Neverwell, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mrs. Neverwell, blockhead! An|&s;wer me, Label, don't you know I've got the Ten thou&s;and pound prize?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>How, Sir! Ten thou&s;and pound!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, 2, 5, 3, 8!&mdash;And now I tell you &mdash;if ever you &s;peak a word more to me about fits or phy&s;ic again, I'll poi&s;on ye, ye dog!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poi&s;on me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I'll poi&s;on you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, I fancy you won't venture to do that.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not venture! pray why not?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e you'll be afraid I &s;hall re|pay you in kind.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! do you pretend to enter the li&s;ts with me in my profe&s;&s;ion! in the Artc Necandi.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>And why not pray? I believe I can lay claim to as many pretty little acci|dents as your&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed! how &s;o, pray?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes indeed! and you reap'd the benefit of 'em; Who d'ye think made all the Mayor's family &s;ick, when you got &s;o many fees from 'em, one after another?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, who?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who but I&mdash;Mon&s;ieur Frican|deau, the French cook, was my old acquain|tance;
<PB N="18" REF="17">&s;o, under pretence of recommending him &s;ome very nice &s;auce for the Mayor that I bought him, I whipt in a little &s;accha|rum &s;aturni, and gave the whole family the co|lic. If you recollect, by making a very &s;light encrea&s;e of their di&s;order at the beginning you kept 'em under your care for nine weeks.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, yes; that was a &s;nug job, I mu&s;t own.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Therefore, Sir, if you're retiring from bu&s;ine&s;s, I &s;hou'd be glad if you'd plea&s;e to reccommend me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Label, you &s;hall &s;ucceed me&mdash;Aris &s;ecundus Apollo&mdash;you &s;hall be the &s;econd Apollo.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank ye, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>I herewith inve&s;t you with the in&s;ig|nia of wi&s;dom&mdash;take my cane&mdash;take my hat &mdash;take my wig&mdash;take my coat, wai&s;tcoat&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>But have not you promis'd to go to Mr. Caddy's this morning, Sir? you won't go without your wig, will you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's true, Label&mdash;I mu&s;t go once more as an apothecary&mdash;poh! But never more will I look on a gallipot&mdash;you &s;hall never more know me to have
<HI>been</HI> an apothecary.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not know you! Lord ble&s;s you! why I &s;hou'd know you all the world over for an apothecary by your talk.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>But you &s;hall now &s;ee the difference &mdash;you &s;hall never hear from my mouth a &s;ingle word that &s;hall remind you of phy&s;ic; for
<PB N="19" REF="18">certainly nothing is &s;o vulgar as for a man's conver&s;ation to &s;mell of his &s;hop!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord, Sir, you've begun already! &mdash;Ha! ha! ha! why that's &s;ecundum artem&mdash; "Smell of your &s;hop;"</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why did I &s;ay &s;o?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh yes you did.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did I Smell of my &s;hop! well it was the la&s;t motion of phy&s;ic within my lips; now be &s;ure you don't let a tittle of my Ten thou|&s;and pound pa&s;s through you to any one liv|ing &mdash;I'll &s;urprize 'em with the &s;udden eclat &mdash;break out on the whole family&mdash;&s;o d'ye hear, Label, if any patients &s;end to me for medicines or advice, tell 'em to take notice &mdash;<HI>take</HI>&mdash;no, plague on't&mdash;that <HI>take</HI> is an apo|thecary's word&mdash;&s;mells of the &s;hop too&mdash;tell 'em to take&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>At it again, Sir&mdash;take&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damnation! tell 'em to take them|&s;elves about their bu&s;ine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> BOY <HI>with a Ba&s;ket.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>BOY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Some bottles, Sir, for your &s;hop!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damn the bottles! and the &s;hop!</P>
<STAGE>(Kicks 'em out of the Boy's hand.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>There now, &s;ee what a number of bottles.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damn all numbers but 2, 5, 3, 8!&mdash; Throw phy&s;ic to the dogs&mdash;2, 5, 3, 8&mdash;Ten thou&s;and pounds:</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit, kicking of basket and breaking the bottles on the &s;helf as he goes off: Label and Boy run off.</STAGE>
<STAGE><PB N="20" REF="19">
SCENE, <HI>a Parlour at</HI> CADDY'S.</STAGE>
<STAGE>&mdash;<HI>Enter</HI> CADDY <HI>with a Letter, followed by Mrs</HI> CADDY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here! here's a fellow throws him&s;elf on my genero&s;ity:</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why &s;urely nothing can be hand&s;omer than Mr. Heartwell's behaviour in writing thus to you,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>And what do you think he does it for? Becau&s;e he does not want my girl with|out her fortune.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>And no one is more de&s;erving of her fortune and her too.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>But he &s;han't have it tho'&mdash;no, no, trade got it, and let trade keep it; I'll have my daughter happy in my own way&mdash;Mr. Lenitive is a proper orderly young man, in a good bu&s;ine&s;s; a man of &s;cience and good ta&s;te. Do you know that he has promis'd to &s;end me a true old Chine&s;e Bonze to-day?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Old Bonze; hav'nt you old bones enough of your own already?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poh, poh; But where's Caroline all this time?&mdash;Caroline&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> CAROLINE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did you want me, papa?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure I do; Look here hu&s;&s;y; you know Mr. Heartwell's hand, I &s;uppo&s;e?</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>&s;hews the letter.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh dear, yes, that I do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="21" REF="20">
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Didn't I charge you, before you left town, when I retired to this &s;eat, which I came to entirely on your account; didn't I &mdash;I &s;ay, charge you to break off all acquaint|ance with Mr. Heartwell, becau&s;e he had not money enough to &s;upport you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes papa; and you charg'd me <HI>before</HI> we left town to <HI>lo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"></HI> Mr. Heartwell; and, as you chang'd your mind once, I hop'd you might do the &s;ame again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>No je&s;ting, hu&s;&s;y; did not I bring all my family into this retired part of the country, that we might not be plagu'd with his vi&s;its; and that he might not even know where to find us?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, papa; and it being &s;o <HI>retired</HI> a part of the country, I wi&s;h'd for Mr. Heartwell to keep me company.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why you impudent!&mdash;harkee, hu&s;&s;y hav'nt I done all this to make you happy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't know, papa; we differ &s;trange|ly in our ideas of happine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>How, minx! an't I always trying to make you happy, if you wou'd but be &s;o: but I can't per&s;uade you to be happy in my way, hav'nt I found for you, here in the country; a &s;uitable hu&s;band in Mr. Lenitive&mdash;a &s;en&s;i|ble &mdash;re&s;pectable&mdash;agreeable&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heigho!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>There again; why, hu&s;&s;y, one wou'd think I was a&s;king you to take his phy&s;ic in|&s;tead of him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="22" REF="21">
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why indeed papa, his phy&s;ic is the mo&s;t agreeable of the two; and you know this Mr. Lenitive&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is a man after my own heart; &s;o don't &s;ay a word again&s;t him; you know that a value I have for him; you'll thank me the longe&s;t day of your life for procuring you &s;uch a hu&s;band&mdash;Oh, here he comes; Now let me &s;ee how well you can behave to him.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LENITIVE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mrs. Caddy, your mo&s;t devoted&mdash;Mr Caddy, I'm your's&mdash;My charming amiable Mi&s;s Caroline, your mo&s;t en&s;lav'd&mdash;you &s;eem divinely well this morning&mdash;your looks are the very &s;yrup of ro&s;es&mdash;you're a happy man Mr. Caddy, in being the father of &s;uch a &s;weet young lady&mdash;I prote&s;t the very &s;ight warms my heart like a cardamum:</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Filthy fellow;&mdash;Mr. Lenitive, your love always puts me in mind of your &s;hop.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, damn the &s;hop; why what did I &s;ay, Mi&s;s, did I &s;peak about my &s;hop?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, you compar'd me to a drug, and &s;aid I warm'd your heart like a cardamum.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did I; oh plague of my apothecary's vocabulary.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>retires up.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Harkee, Mi&s;s, if you're come back to your &s;en&s;es, I advi&s;e you to look on Mr. Lenitive as your hu&s;band that is to be; and if you have not yet recover'd 'em, I'll &s;end him to ye as a phy&s;ician.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="23" REF="22">
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, papa, I'll take him as a phy&s;ician.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, you're not ill, are you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, but I &s;oon &s;hou'd be if he were my hu&s;band: and then I mu&s;t take him for both,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Caroline, I'm a&s;ham'd of ye.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pardon me, Mr. Caddy&mdash;Pray, Mi&s;s Caroline&mdash;if I may make bold to feel the pul&s;e of your inclinations, what can you find to di&s;like in me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why; I di&s;like you on the whole. Is not that enough.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>But what do you di&s;like about me in particular?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why I don't like your wig.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>My wig! don't like my wig! fanci|ful enough! Well, that perhaps time&mdash;how I long to tell her&mdash;but mum&mdash;I &s;hall &s;urprize 'em this afternoon, but what el&s;e do you di&s;like?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't like your coat.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't like my coat! my wig and my coat, my dear Mi&s;s Caroline, perhaps, I &s;ay no more at pre&s;ent, but perhaps time may mend'em</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I don't like your face.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, damn it! time won't mend that!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear Mr. Lenitive, excu&s;e this girl &mdash;&s;he's young and fooli&s;h at pre&s;ent&mdash;Caro|line, an't you a&s;ham'd of yourself? Mr, Leni|tive's dre&s;s is &s;uited to his profe&s;&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Profe&s;&s;ion&mdash;fogh! I can't bear to hear it mentioned.
<STAGE>(<HI>A&s;ide</HI>)</STAGE>, I'll go directly to Whip&s;titch, the taylor, and equip my&s;elf in
<PB N="24" REF="23">the pink of the mode.&mdash;Mr. Caddy, you'll excu&s;e me&mdash;particular bu&s;ine&s;s&mdash;Mi&s;s Caro|line &mdash;&s;uffer me from tho&s;e bright eyes to take one emollient draught of comfort&mdash;plague on the words of my &s;hop&mdash;they &s;tick to my tongue like a bli&s;ter.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>going</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, Mr. Lenitive, you won't forget the Bonze?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hoeret lateri, Mr. Caddy; I'll &s;et in in&s;tantly in motion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>You'll think of me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh mihi po&s;t nullos Caddi memo|randi &s;odales&mdash;2, 5, 3, 8.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit with</HI> Mrs. Caddy.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>There now! there's a hu&s;band for ye&mdash;none of your Heart well's for me, hark'ee, did not you &s;end word to Heartwell of the place we are retired to?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Me, papa! not I!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, I know you did&mdash;you have no regard to the pains I take to make you happy&mdash;I wonder, if I was to di&s;inherit you for your perver&s;ene&s;s, whether Heartwell wou'd travel as far to find you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, papa, I'm &s;ure he wou'd&mdash;be|cau&s;e &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, becau&s;e why, pray?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e he told me him&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's a good rea&s;on indeed! No, no, I fancy we &s;hou'd not be troubled with many of his vi&s;its then.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nor Mr. Lenitive's either.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="25" REF="24">
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now don't make me angry, or I'll di&s;inherit you in earne&s;t, and leave your for|tune to your cou&s;in Clara, who is expected here in a few days.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now my dear papa! I have hit on a &s;cheme which you mu&s;t a&s;&s;i&s;t me to put in practice; after which, if you de&s;ire it, I am willing to marry Mr. Lenitive.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>A &s;cheme! non&s;en&s;e! what &s;cheme is it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Only to inform Mr. Heartwell and Mr. Lenitive, that you have di&s;inherited me, and &s;ettled your fortune on my cou&s;in Clara; then &s;uffer me to pa&s;s for her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then we may make trial of 'em both, and find which is the mo&s;t di&s;intere&s;ted; and &s;ee who's in the right, you or I,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, and if Heartwell makes love to the &s;uppos'd cou&s;in&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll marry Lenitive as &s;oon as you plea&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, you little fool! then you'll be married to-morrow morning.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very well</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>But you don't con&s;ider, that Clara has been &s;o long in France, &s;he has more than half forgot the u&s;e of her native tongue; how then will you pa&s;s for her without being di&s;|covered.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing more ea&s;y; 'tis only dre&s;|&s;ing my&s;elf out like an Opera dancer, to&s;&s;ing
<PB N="26" REF="25">my head, and imitating the French.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hark'e, Caroline, you may imitate your cou&s;in's affectation, and to&s;s your head about as much as you plea&s;e; but as long as I have a leg to &s;tand on, I promi&s;e ye none of my family &s;hall ever imitate the French.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear papa, don't mi&s;conceive me; I mean to di&s;gui&s;e my&s;elf, only by an expo&s;ition of their folly; for, however I may copy their ridicule by this &s;cheme I have in my head, my heart is of true Engli&s;h growth, I a&s;&s;ure ye.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I like the bargain well enouh; I'll &s;end to Lenitive and Heartwell directly; do you get your&s;elf ready, and mind our agreement.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>That I will, mo&s;t rigidly; but if my plot fails, I'll willingly relingui&s;h all hopes of happine&s;s with my lover.</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT>
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG.</HEAD>
<LG>
<L>Oh, dear delightful &s;kill,</L>
<L>The wily part to play,</L>
<L>And lead the &s;wain at will,</L>
<L>I think I know the way;</L>
<L>With tears and &s;ighs</L>
<L>I'll now &s;urpri&s;e,</L>
<L>Now pleas'd awhile,</L>
<L>With &s;miles beguile,</L>
<L>And fairly gain the day,</L>
<L>For I think I know the way.</L>
<L><PB N="27" REF="26">
While mi&s;tre&s;s of my art,</L>
<L>Each rule I know &s;o pat,</L>
<L>To &s;way a lover's heart,</L>
<L>Leave me alone for that.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>At &s;chool when all wou'd try</L>
<L>Our governe&s;s to cheat,</L>
<L>Then who &s;o well as I</L>
<L>Cou'd manage the deceit?</L>
<L>With look &s;o &s;ly,</L>
<L>No, &s;ure, not I;</L>
<L>Dear Ma'am, not me,</L>
<L>It cou'd not be!</L>
<L>You know I'm too di&s;creet&mdash;</L>
<L>Dear Ma'am, it cou'd not be, &amp;c. &amp;c.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit.</HI>)</STAGE>
<TRAILER>END OF THE FIRST ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="act">
<PB N="28" REF="27">
<HEAD>ACT II.</HEAD>
<STAGE>SCENE,&mdash;<HI>Caddy's Mu&s;eum</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE>&mdash;<HI>Enter Mr. and</HI> Mrs. CADDY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>POOR Caroline! this matter will &s;oon be &s;ettled; &s;he'll &s;carcely go from her word: and I'm &s;ure of Lenitive. So, thank Hea|ven, my girl will be happy at la&s;t in the way I wou'd have her.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>A noi&s;e without</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hey-day! what is all that noi&s;e on the &s;tair-ca&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SERVANT.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERV.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, Mr. Lenitive's compliments to you and Mi&s;s Caroline, and he has &s;ent two ca&s;es.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, my dear, he &s;ent me word he
<PB N="29" REF="28">hop'd to pre&s;ent me with a &s;econd ca&s;e, which I &s;hou'd e&s;teem a no le&s;s valuable curio&s;ity than the fir&s;t; another Bonze I &s;uppo&s;e; this is a &s;on-in-law after my own heart; no &s;op|peries &mdash;no &s;ineries&mdash;Oh, here they come&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> MEN <HI>with two Mummy Ca&s;es, which they &s;et down and Exit.</HI></STAGE>
<P>And here's Mr. Lenitive&mdash;eh! No, its Label!</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LABEL <HI>dre&s;s'd exactly as</HI> LENITIVE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, friend, I was in hopes of &s;ee|ing your ma&s;ter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>Ma&s;ter,</HI> Sir, <HI>Ma&s;ter</HI>!&mdash;Sir, Mr. Lenitive will be here pre&s;ently&mdash;any com|plaints in the family, Sir? as Mr. Lenitive is retiring from bu&s;ine&s;s, I &s;hou'd be glad to be employ'd during the
<HI>re&s;iduum</HI> of your days, Sir&mdash;you may depend on con&s;tant attendance, rea&s;onable bills, and a Copia Me|dicinorum, Opitmorum, and Santiffimorum.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Con&s;tant attendance! Why damme, Sir, d'ye think I mean to be&s;peak di&s;orders as I do my &s;hoes, and be ill by the year! Get out of my &s;ight directly!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>An old frump! but he's a good cu&s;tomer, and &s;o&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide muttering and retiring up.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>An impudent puppy! His ma&s;ter re|tiring! No, no, his ma&s;ter is not &s;uch a fool, Now, my dear&mdash;let me &s;ee&mdash;Oh, Lord, here's
<PB N="30" REF="29">Heartwell, plague on him for coming ju&s;t at this moment! he &s;han't have a &s;ight of the Chine&s;e Bonzes, though I long to &s;ee'em my&s;elf, but they are too &s;acred for the eyes of a fop.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> HEARTWELL <HI>in Regimentals.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Heartwell, your &s;ervant!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is it po&s;&s;ible, Sir, I can be &s;o fortunate as&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>I gue&s;s what you're going to &s;ay, Sir; but you can't gue&s;s what I'm going to &s;ay to you, and &s;o I'll tell you&mdash;You mu&s;t know, Sir, you'll be &s;upris'd&mdash;but Caroline's perver&s;e behaviour has, at la&s;t, induced me to transfer my affections to my niece Clara, to whom I have made over all the fortune I formerly de|&s;ign'd for Caroline.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>How, Sir! Di&s;inherited your own daughter!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir; di&s;inherited my own daughter! I &s;uppo&s;e I may do what I will with my own? Oh ho! what that alters the ca&s;e, does it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, if you meant only to in&s;ult me&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>In&s;ult you! no, Sir; I &s;ent for you only out of re&s;pect to you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, yes, Sir; I &s;ent for you to offer you my niece Clara's hand, it you chu&s;e her, in&s;tead of Caroline's: why, you'd &s;carce know
<PB N="31" REF="30">one from the other, except that Clara is more accompli&s;h'd from having been educated abroad, and not &s;o homely as Caroline.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>How, Sir; do you think to make &s;port of me like an ideot? Be a&s;&s;ured, Sir, your niece's accompli&s;hments are no object to me&mdash;but where is my dear Caroline? no force &s;hall keep her from me&mdash;her poverty &s;hall be my pride&mdash;and the profit of my commi&s;&s;ion, though &s;mall, &s;hall be lavi&s;h'd on her, and every effort &s;train'd to make her happy as her merit de&s;erves, and &s;o, Sir, your &s;ervant,</P>
<STAGE>(exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, your &s;ervant Sir, what I &s;uppo&s;e he'd per&s;uade me that if he was rich he'd marry Caroline without a fortune&mdash;but I know the world a little too well, but now, my dear Mrs. Caddy, how I long to &s;ee 'em;
<STAGE>Opens Ca&s;e and di&s;covers a black deform'd Chine&s;e Jo&s;s.</STAGE>
There's No1. &mdash;I never &s;aw a greater beau|ty; it's enough to frighten one to look at it&punc; what awe it in&s;pires! ay, ay, this is the pride of my intended &s;on-in-law; he's fonder of this than the whole female race, now Heartwell's a fool; fond of nothing but wine, women, and &s;uch trumpery&mdash;no &s;en&s;e, no ta&s;te&mdash;Now if the other be but as great a curio&s;ity&mdash;if No. 2.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Opens Ca&s;e.</HI> LENITIVE&punc; <HI>bolts out with the Lot|tery Ticket in his hand.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Number Two Thou&s;and Five Hun|dred and Thirty Eight; bought at Richard&s;on
<PB N="32" REF="31">and Goodluck's, Charing Cro&s;s, oppo&s;ite the man upon the Black Hor&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why what the devil is all this, Mr. Lenitive?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Caddy, fortune, who too often confers her favours blindly, has this day di&s;|played her &s;uperior ta&s;te by &s;electing me for her favourite: I come in this manner to offer to your family an e&s;tate of Ten thou&s;and pounds principal money. Of the many ca&s;es I have been engaged in, I have come out of this in the mo&s;t brilliant manner,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah. I had rather have had another old Bonze.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>I flatter my&s;elf this humour of mine breaking out quite in a new vein&mdash;this dre&s;s&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dre&s;s; why you look like a Tom fool why what the deuce do you mean by this lit|tle jacket?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Little jacket; why that's my great coat</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Great coat.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, great coat, every body wear the&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why who the deuce makes &s;uch great coats?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who? why Whip&s;titch, the London taylor?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Whip&s;titch&mdash;where does he live?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>On the &s;kirts of the town.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>But where's the charming young lady, Mr. Caddy, who has the honour to be your niece?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, you heard all about it then while you was in the ca&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="33" REF="32">
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>With a&s;toni&s;hment!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, I have my rea&s;ons for it; and egad I &s;u&s;pect one more than I thought&mdash; Well, what &s;ay you; Caroline without a for|tune, or Clara with one? I give you your choice&mdash;that is, provided you return to your old coat and wig.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pardon me, Mr. Caddy, pray drop the idea of the old coat and wig! the &s;tomach turns at the bare remembrane.</P>
</SP>
<Q><TEXT>
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>DUET.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<L>From my hide and &s;eek chin,</L>
<L>Sometimes out, &s;ometimes in,</L>
<L>How fla&s;hy my mu&s;lin ca&s;cade is!</L>
<L>The pul&s;e no more I &s;queeze,</L>
<L>But &s;oftly as you plea&s;e;</L>
<L>I now &s;queeze the hand of the ladies,</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<L>To all who complain,</L>
<L>Here, I hold out my cane,</L>
<L>For Label a knight of the trade is;</L>
<L>No hand &s;o fair to me,</L>
<L>As the hand that holds a fee,</L>
<L>And I care not a pin for the ladies.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<L>See my gold cane and wig</L>
<L>I've hung upon a peg,</L>
<L><PB N="34" REF="33">
Hic coe&s;tus urturque repono;</L>
<L>Gentility's my plan,</L>
<L>And I leave my journeyman</L>
<L>The care of the Publico Bono.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<L>The world if you try,</L>
<L>Fir&s;t of Doctors am I,</L>
<L>For ills that I know, and I don't know,</L>
<L>Deny it if you can,</L>
<L>Little Label is the man</L>
<L>To take care of the Publico Bono.</L>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
</TEXT></Q>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exeunt.</HI>)</STAGE>
<STAGE>SCENE,&mdash;<HI>Another Chamber at Caddy's.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> HEARTWELL.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll not leave the hou&s;e till I find this apothecary; at his &s;hop they a&s;&s;ured me he was here; be&s;ides, in waiting I may have a chance of &s;eeing my dear Caroline&mdash;Eh! who comes here?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LENITIVE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Cou&s;in; Caroline&mdash;take the cou&s;in in&s;tead of Caroline&mdash;Love is a very pretty in|gredient in a match to be &s;ure: but love and fortune make a much plea&s;anter mixture.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your &s;ervant, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Whom have we hear! Heartwell again? Zounds! how he's recover'd &s;ince I left
<PB N="35" REF="34">him&mdash;He certainly has not taken his phy&s;ic.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh! is that my rival yonder&mdash;he's &s;trangely alter'd in his appcarance&mdash;Your &s;er|vant, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, your &s;ervant!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>May I pre&s;ume to a&s;k Sir, if your name is not Lenitive, the apothecary?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lenitive, Sir&mdash;Luke Lenitive, E&s;q. at your &s;ervice: but apothecary no more.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hear, Sir, that Mr. Caddy has &s;ome thoughts of marrying his daughter to you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>You hear &s;o&mdash;He! he! he! I believe Sir, there may be &s;om thoughts of &s;uch a thing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Have you the lady's con&s;ent Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>The lady's con&s;ent! Ha! ha! ha! egad that's plea&s;ant enough! I &s;hou'd think any one that look'd at my figure&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your figure's as ridiculous as I conceive your pretentions to be; you look to me like&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Like what, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Like an apothecary.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Devil I do!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>And let me advi&s;e you, Mr, Apo|thecary, to be cautious how you proceed! or you'll have more bu&s;ine&s;s to &s;ettle than you are aware of.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I've left my bu&s;ine&s;s! but pray, Captain, have you any right to pre&s;cribe to me? I've got Ten thou&s;and pound in my pocket, that's more than every gentleman of the army can boa&s;t,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hark'e, Mr. Whipper&s;napper, if
<PB N="36" REF="35">you, &s;uffer Mr. Caddy to lay the lea&s;t &s;hadow of re&s;traint on his daughter's inclinations, the only choice I &s;hall leave you will be, the length of your ground the pi&s;tol-&s;hot.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Egad, then I'll chu&s;e a &s;ufficient long one.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>But why do I talk of a pi&s;tol to a fellow that de&s;erves to be pounded in his own mortar?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let me advi&s;e you, Sir, to be on your guard! how vou in&s;ult a gentleman with &s;uch language&mdash;Whipper&s;napper indeed! you'll find, Sir. that if once I take hold of a pi&s;tol&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>A pi&s;tol! a pe&s;tle you mean?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Sir, a pi&s;tol&mdash;I mean, a pi&s;tol&mdash; P, I, S, T, O, L&mdash;I &s;ay, Sir, if once I take a pe&s;tle&mdash;a pi&s;tol I mean&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>There, you &s;ee now&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Plague of my tongue&mdash;I &s;ay, Sir, if once I take hold of a pi&s;tol&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! ha! ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>What d'ye laugh at, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>I beg your pardon, Sir&mdash;But I was thinking, as I have e&s;cap'd &s;afe from your medicines, I need not much be afraid of any thing el&s;e I can receive from you: you'll re|member my advice&mdash;Your mo&s;t obedient, Doctor Apothecary.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Exit</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Doctor! Damnation! Oh that ever I &s;hou'd have ever been an apothecary!&mdash;Ecod it wou'd be a neat trick enough to take the cou&s;in, and fob this Copper Captain off with a girl without a &s;ixpence&mdash;&s;ee who'll laugh
<PB N="37" REF="36">then&mdash;Doctor indeed! I'll Doctor him&mdash;Oh, here is Mr. Caddy&mdash;Well, Sir, what news of the young lady?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> CADDY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Take care of your heart, Mr. Leni|tive &mdash;egad &s;he'll make a conque&s;t of you&mdash;I have a great mind to give him a hint of the trick&mdash;Yonder &s;he comes, d'ye &s;ee her! &s;he's as like Caroline as one nankeen beaker is like another.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN. <HI>(Cro&s;&s;es to, and looks thro' his gla&s;s.)</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Egad as you &s;ay, they're as like as two pills out of the &s;ame box.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>D'ye think &s;he's as hand&s;ome?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hand&s;omer!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't like that&mdash; <STAGE>(<HI>a&s;ide.</HI>)</STAGE> But, Caro|line is the better match for all that&mdash;Well, here &s;he comes&mdash;I'll leave ye together&mdash;but remember you had better take Caroline.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Take Caroline without a fortune&mdash; No&mdash;marriage without money is, as the Song &s;ays, "Bitter to &s;wallow, and hard of dige&s;tion."</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> CAROLINE.</STAGE>
<STAGE>(skims acro&s;s)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, ma chere bon amie la jolie Garcon!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Egad this is the very thing for me! quite the &s;hapes for a man of my fortune&mdash;how lucky that I'm a gentleman! I wi&s;h &s;he &s;poke Engli&s;h though, that I might under&s;tand her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Mon&s;ieur Lenitive, comme e&s;t Beau&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="38" REF="37">
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>A Beau! yes, I am that! &s;he's &s;truck with my figure&mdash;Yes, &s;he has a good ta&s;te&mdash;egad &s;he's the fir&s;t per&s;on I've found in the hou&s;e who has any.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Mon&s;ieur, qui'l e&s;t a Beau,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Kill a beau! no, Mi&s;s&mdash;I've cur'd many&mdash;never kill'd one in all my life&mdash;Oh, &s;he means that I &s;hall die for love of her&mdash;Yes, lovely charmer, in that your charms are more dangerous than medicine&mdash;they are &s;ufficient to unnerve the fibres of the &s;tronge&s;t heart&mdash; pierce the integuments of the perricordium; and penetrate quite thro' the &s;olids into the medulla&mdash;Zounds! this unlucky jargon is al|ways at my tongue's end!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mon&s;ieur, you &s;peak a to me of phy&s;ic.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, &s;he has &s;melt me out&mdash;I mu&s;st alter my &s;y&s;tem&mdash;Pray, Mi&s;s Clara, did you ever &s;ee me before?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oui tres &s;ouvent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>What's that you &s;ay, Mi&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Je parle Francois?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Mi&s;s I don't parley in Francoi&s;e &mdash;Damn it, that's unlucky too, now I'm a gentleman!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Parle Italiano?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Mi&s;s, I don't &s;peak French at all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>No. I believe all languages are alike to him.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>a&s;ide</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>What d'ye &s;ay, Mi&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Que vous etes charmante.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, nor Jarman&mdash;I &s;peak all the dead languages but French and Jarman!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="39" REF="38">
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, ce ne maimex pas.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Mi&s;s, it's you have maimed me in the heart, and mu&s;t now be my phy&s;ician.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, I fear you no love a me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>I entreat you Mi&s;s, to throw off tho&s;e fears&mdash;
<STAGE>(<HI>Kneels</HI>)</STAGE>, Suffer me to a&s;&s;ure you, Mi&s;s, that nothing can root out my pa&s;&s;ion&mdash;I am po&s;itive that neither change of air nor diet cou'd give me the &s;malle&s;t relief&mdash;No, Mi&s;s, the fever of love is &s;o &s;trong upon me, that I'm certain &s;ixteen grains of James's powders wou'd have no more effect than&mdash;Damnit, I'm nail'd to the counter like a bad &s;hilling.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>ri&s;es</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, pitie pauvre Caroline, who will be &s;o much di&s;appoint of &s;o &s;weet a gentilhomme.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh dear no; di&s;appointment perhaps may di&s;order her &s;tomach&mdash;occa&s;ion bile&mdash; but that's all&mdash;I'll venture to a&s;&s;ert that a lit|tle &s;al polycre&s;t and rhubarb, taking regularly three table &s;poons full, four or five times a day&mdash;Zounds, I've got into my &s;hop again!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;ee my cou&s;in no more den?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh your cou&s;in, Mi&s;s, wou'd not have done for me at all&mdash;very well in the country, but wou'd not do to hang upon my arm in the great world&mdash;But when we go to London we shall &s;ee the Italian Opeara, and hear Moun&s;eer Browni, Signor Kelly, madam Mary, and Sig|nora Scratchi&mdash;and then we &s;hall vi&s;it all the polite place&mdash;Vauxhall Gardens, Apollo Gar|dens, Bermond&s;ey Spa&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah you make de belle figure.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>A figure? Oh yes, 2, 5, 3, 8, for that.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="40" REF="39">
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Vil you dance a chaccone vid me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray excu&s;e me, Mi&s;s, I never danc'd in my life&mdash;except after my patients.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>a&s;ide,</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Vil you &s;ing?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Mi&s;s, when I &s;ing&mdash;I&mdash;I don't often &s;ing when I do they&mdash;they&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, moque de vous!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, they &s;moke me&mdash;they laugh at me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>If you plea&s;e I &s;ing a you de Canzo|net and grand Air from the Opera at Paris.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh Lord, ay! that mu&s;t be charming!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<STAGE>CAROLINE <HI>&s;ings.</HI></STAGE>
<L>Beaux yeaux, qui cau&s;er mon trepas</L>
<L>Revenez en ces lieux pour finer mon martire,</L>
<L>Depuis votre depart je languis je &s;oupire,</L>
<L>Quand vous me dites good bye ju&s;queau revoir;</L>
<L>How grieve mou coeur leave me en di&s;&s;efpoir,</L>
<L>Farewel plai&s;ir, no joy till vot retour;</L>
<L>Ah! pitie quelque unto my tendre amour,</L>
<L>Je meurs pour vos divins appas et je no&s;e.</L>
<STAGE>(<HI>Sung to the height of Burle&s;que and Ridicule.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, charming! &s;uch melody! &s;uch words! tho' damn me if I under&s;tood one of 'em!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(<HI>A&s;ide, and retires up &s;oothing</HI> CAROLINE.)</STAGE>
<STAGE><PB N="41" REF="40">
<HI>Enter</HI> JUBA <HI>with a Letter, following</HI> CADDY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't a&s;k me about your ma&s;ter!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JUBA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh me &s;o glad! &s;o glad&mdash;Ma&s;&s;a no here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, I tell you&mdash;He has been gone this half hour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JUBA.</SPEAKER>
<P>Den me find him&mdash;dis letter make my Ma&s;&s;a &s;o happy!</P>
<STAGE>(Exit.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Mr. Lenitive, how d'ye find your&s;elf? what, you're &s;mitten, are you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, enchanted!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>And you are willing to take Clara in|&s;tead of my daughter, are you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>With raptures! My dear Mr. Caddy, there's as much difference between her and your daughter as between honey and hieri picra&mdash;Mi&s;s Clara has more wit, more life, more &s;pirit, more air, more&mdash;every thing&mdash; &s;he is &s;al volatile it&s;elf!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now if it was not for the Chine&s;e Bonze he gave me, I cou'd kick him
<STAGE>(A&s;ide)</STAGE> Hey-day! Heartwell here again.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> HEARTWELL <HI>with a Letter.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, what do you come for now, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>I return to you with a heart pant|ing with hope: the intelligence I have here re|ceiv'd, enables me to offer Mi&s;s Caroline, with my hand, a fortune &s;uperior to that which was once her own. I am ready to take her
<PB N="42" REF="41">without a &s;hilling, and only reque&s;t to receive her from your hand.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear papa! who's in the right now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HEART.</SPEAKER>
<P>How! Caroline!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>What Caroline!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, this was all a trick of Caroline's! but you had not &s;en&s;e enough to &s;ee it&mdash;you &s;on of a Gallipot!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>So I've made a pretty job of it!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Conver&s;ation in dumb &s;how between</HI> CAROLINE, HEARTWELL, <HI>and</HI> CADDY.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LABEL <HI>with a Letter,</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Lenitive, here's another letter for you, brought to <HI>my &s;hop,</HI> from the Lottery Office.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, they've &s;ent me a draft for the money, well this will con&s;ole me for my lo&s;s of credit here.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Reads</HI>&mdash;</STAGE>
<LETTER>
<OPENER><SALUTE>SIR,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>We are &s;orry to be under the di&s;agreeable nece&s;&s;ity of&mdash;</P>
<P>What's all this! of apologizing to you, for the unfortunate mi&s;take of a
<HI>Figure</HI> in your Lottery Ticket, which was not the number of the Prize, but was immediately afterward drawn.
<PB N="43" REF="42">No. 2, 5, 3, 8, was drawn a Blank, but 2, 5, 8, 3, drawn a Prize of Ten Thou&s;and Pounds; was &s;old by Bran&s;comb and Bi&s;h, at their Lucky Office, next the Striking Conjurors, at St. Dun&s;tan's.</P>
</LETTER>
</SP>
<P>Damnation! my Prize is a Blank!</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>OMNES.</SPEAKER>
<P>A Blank! Ha! ha! ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>How, Sir! a blank?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>There's a mi&s;take in a figure?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>What in 2, 5, 3, 8?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh cur&s;e 2, 5, 3, 8!&mdash;I'll tell you what, Label, I'll have my coat and wig again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LABEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>No you don't tho'&mdash;I'm in po&s;&s;e&s;|&s;ion, and that you know&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Runs off.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LEN.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will have my wig, if I get no|thing el&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(<HI>Snatching at</HI> LABEL'S <HI>wig as he runs off.</HI>)</STAGE>
<L>Yes, I'll now re&s;ume pill, pe&s;tle, potion, powder, drop,</L>
<L>And all the former jargon of my &s;hop:</L>
<L>Return to Galen, Cel&s;us, Hippocrates,</L>
<L>Since now a Gallipot my whole e&s;tate is,</L>
<L>With Lotteries now for ever I'll have done,</L>
<L>Forget 2, 5, 3, 8, and &s;tick to Number One.</L>
<STAGE><PB N="44" REF="43">
FINALE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CAR.</SPEAKER>
<L>The changling's fate we've &s;et to view,</L>
<L>Our own depends alone on you;</L>
<L>To night, if we your &s;miles obtain,</L>
<L>We've drawn the Prize we &s;ought to gai</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>CHORUS.</SPEAKER>
<L>With anxious hearts we look about,</L>
<L>To &s;ee if Prize or Blank come out;</L>
<L>More vain of you, than fortune kind.</L>
<L>Since you can &s;ee, and &s;he is blind.</L>
</SP>
</DIV2>
<TRAILER>FINIS.</TRAILER>
</DIV1>
